  <h3><i class="mch-compass-2"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-compass-3.jpg" alt="Image of Compass" class="right ppic" />RELATE. Strategies to Enable Effective Implementation</h3>

<p>In this section, reflect on how you can implement this competency in your daily work. To help with this process, review these <strong>five implementation strategies</strong>.</p>
<h3>Tiered Approach</h3>
<p>These implementation strategies follow a <strong>tiered approach of widening circles of influence</strong>. Through this approach, MCH leaders utilize resources and tools to activate change within their organization, which in turn incorporates partners through its systems of influence. Together, changes may be implemented to affect specific target populations and the MCH community in general. </p>
<p><img src="../../images/spheres-of-influence.png" alt="Implementation Model" width="1956" height="700"/></p>
<h3>Implementation Strategies</h3>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> <strong>Self-Reflection Strategy. </strong>How to advance yourself as an MCH leader.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Advance Yourself as an MCH Leader (Self-Reflection Strategy)</strong>. Identify your personal strengths and areas of growth by taking 5 minutes to register/log-in to the MCH Navigator's <a href="../../assessment/index.php">Self-Assessment</a> and answer questions related to Competency 10: Interdisciplinary Team Building.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>Information Strategy. </strong>How to find and use tools to help you.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Find and Use Tools to Help You (Information Strategy)</strong>. The <a href="https://nexusipe.org/">National Center for Interprofessional Practice and Education</a>, housed at the University of Minnesota, leads, coordinates, and studies the advancement of collaborative, team-based health professions education and patient care as an efficient model for improving quality, outcomes, and cost. It is a public-private partnership with the Health Resources and Services Administration (HRSA) and three private foundations. You can <em><strong>assess your understanding of interprofessional collaboration and practice in different settings</strong></em> with the Center's curated  <a href="https://nexusipe.org/advancing/assessment-evaluation">collection of&nbsp;measurement tools</a>&nbsp;(use menu on the left to filter tools) and <em><strong>get ideas for supporting your interprofessional teams</strong></em> through their <a href="https://nexusipe.org/informing/literature-compendium">review of the literature</a>. </p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-university"></i> <strong>Organizational Strategy. </strong>How to activate your organization.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Activate Your Organization (Organizational Strategy)</strong>. The guiding principles, practices, and case examples described in<a href="https://nexusipe-resource-exchange.s3.amazonaws.com/Lessons%20from%20the%20Field%20-%20Promising%20Interprofessional%20Collaboration%20Practices.pdf"> this report</a> funded by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation describes ways to<em><strong> address and overcome many of the historical barriers to interprofessional collaboration</strong></em>. <a href="https://www.ahrq.gov/teamstepps/index.html">TeamSTEPPS®</a> materials and <a href="https://www.ahrq.gov/teamstepps/officebasedcare/index.html">training curricula</a> present ways to <em><strong>integrate teamwork principles into a variety of settings</strong></em>. <a href="https://www.ahrq.gov/teamstepps/officebasedcare/tools.html">Evaluation materials</a> are also available to measure success. Select a lesson topic and use the video, agenda, and debrief worksheet to conduct an exercise and lead a discussion with your staff.</p>
 
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>Systems Strategy. </strong>How to incorporate partners.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How</strong><strong> to Incorporate Partners (Systems Strategy)</strong>. <em><strong>Youth Transition as an Example of Interprofessional Team Building: </strong></em>As youth leave school, they face several transitions including school to work or postsecondary education, family home to community living, and child-oriented health care to adult care.<em><strong> The range of possible activities and supports required for successful transition requires collaboration and support from many adult-serving agencies and systems</strong></em>. Have you made transition planning a priority in your state or community? If so, do your transition planning strategies include interagency collaboration and/or interprofessional training? <em><strong>For suggestions on refining or updating state objectives and strategies</strong></em>, check out <a href="https://www.gottransition.org/resource/?titlev-hct-performance-2016">this report</a> from the <a href="https://www.gottransition.org">Center for Health Care Transition Improvement (GotTransition?)</a>. A<a href="https://www.gottransition.org/resource/?2023-coding-tip-sheet"> tip sheet</a> on transition coding and reimbursement is also available.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-globe"></i> <strong>Community Strategy. </strong>How to engage your communities.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Engage Your Communities. </strong>The <a href="https://www.kansasmch.org/fac-about.asp">Kansas Bureau of Family Health Family Advisory Council (FAC)</a> is made up of family members and consumers who are interested in helping drive positive changes to maternal and child health services and inform programs for women, children, and families. Since 2009, the FAC has been the primary sounding board to ensure that families&rsquo; needs are met in Bureau of Family Health programming. The FAC has produced family-driven and family-focused brochures, white papers, and fact sheets, including <a href="https://www.kansasmch.org/fac/materials/2016_09_12%20Comm_Partner_FINAL.pdf">Partner and Communicate with Families of Children with Special Health Care Needs</a>.</p>
</div>
</div>  

      
<h2><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> 10.3.2 PRACTICE</h2>
	  <div class="evidenceBorder">
	  <h3><i class="mch-bookmarks"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-reflect.jpg" alt="Image of Thought Bubble" class="right ppic" />REFLECT. Staying Motivated</h3>
	  <p>As you work through your growth in this competency, it's important to stay motivated. Here are some tips to help you maintain focus and productivity along the way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Learn in Groups</strong>. 
          Lifelong learning doesn&rsquo;t mean condemning yourself to a stack of dusty textbooks. Join organizations that teach skills. Workshops and group learning events can make educating yourself a fun, social experience.</li>
        <li><strong>Make Learning a Priority</strong>. 
          Few external forces are going to persuade you to learn. The desire has to come from within. Once you decide you want to make lifelong learning a habit, it is up to you to make it a priority in your life.</li>
        <li><strong>Keep smart company</strong>. 
          Reach out to contacts that you admire. Get talking to some influencers on Twitter and organize to meet up to explore some ideas and learning topics. Make sure to keep in touch with people you have come into contact with who have inspired you to learn on your journey.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><img src="../../images/mch-smart-motivation-10.jpeg" width="1024" height="512" alt="Motivational image" /> </p>
